      <bioghist encodinganalog="545">
         <head>Biographical History</head>
         
      <p>Thomas Mann (1875-1955) was a German novelist, short story writer, social critic, 
		philanthropist and essayist.  He won the 1929 Nobel Prize for Literature for his novels 
		<emph render="italic">Buddenbrooks</emph>, which was also his first novel, and 
		<emph render="italic">The Magic Mountain</emph>.</p></bioghist>
      
      <scopecontent encodinganalog="520">
         <head>Scope and Contents of the Collection</head>
         <p>The <emph render="bold">Thomas Mann Collection</emph> consists of six letters from 
			Mann and one photograph of him.  The letters are to various people and generally 
			concern Mann's writing or his opinion of others' writings.  One gives his assessment of 
			a German language text for English teachers of the German language, another denies the 
			rumor that he had written a play entitled <emph render="italic">Woman of a Hundred Faces</emph>.  
			The photograph is inscribed by Mann, in German, to Dr. Benno Lee of Hunter College.</p>
      </scopecontent>
      
